<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is Morse code?", answer: "Morse code is a method of encoding text characters as sequences of dots (short signals) and dashes (long signals). Invented by Samuel Morse and Alfred Vail in the 1830s for use with the electric telegraph, it assigns unique combinations of dots and dashes to each letter of the alphabet, digit, and some punctuation marks. For example, the letter A is represented as dot-dash (.-), while the letter B is dash-dot-dot-dot (-...). Morse code was the primary means of long-distance communication for over a century." },
  { question: "How does Morse code timing work?", answer: "In standard Morse code, a dash is three times the duration of a dot. The gap between parts of the same letter (dot-dash combinations) equals one dot duration. The gap between letters equals three dot durations. The gap between words equals seven dot durations. In written Morse code, dots and dashes within a letter are written together, letters are separated by spaces, and words are separated by a forward slash (/) or three spaces." },
  { question: "Is Morse code still used today?", answer: "Yes, Morse code remains in use in several contexts. Amateur radio operators (ham radio) use it for long-distance communication, especially in the CW (continuous wave) mode. Aviation uses some Morse code identifiers for navigation aids (VOR and NDB beacons). The international distress signal SOS (... --- ...) is universally recognized. Morse code is also used as an assistive technology for people with disabilities who can communicate through binary inputs like eye blinks or switch presses." },
  { question: "What is the SOS signal in Morse code?", answer: "SOS is the international Morse code distress signal, represented as three dots, three dashes, three dots (... --- ...) sent as a continuous sequence without letter spacing. Contrary to popular belief, SOS does not stand for Save Our Souls or any other phrase. It was chosen in 1906 at the International Radiotelegraph Convention because the pattern is simple, distinctive, and easy to recognize even under poor signal conditions. It replaced the earlier CQD distress signal." },
  { question: "Can Morse code encode any language?", answer: "Standard International Morse Code (ITU Morse) covers the 26 Latin letters, 10 Arabic numerals, and common punctuation marks. Extensions exist for other Latin-script languages with diacritical marks (such as German, French, and Spanish characters), and separate Morse code systems were developed for non-Latin scripts including Russian (Russian Morse code), Japanese (Wabun code), and Korean (SKATS). Chinese does not have a direct Morse encoding but uses a numeric code table where each character is assigned a four-digit number." }
]) %>

